Date: Sat 14 Sep 2013
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Outbreak of bovine anthrax in General Belgrano, Province of Buenos Aires
----------------------------------------------------------------------
During the 2nd week of September 2013, _Bacillus anthracis_ was identified in an adult cow in a herd of 90 head. The death was sudden with an extravasation of blood from its natural openings (mouth, anus, vagina). The herd had been vaccinated with Sterne vaccine over 300 days previously.

The establishment is in the Partido [2nd level administrative division] of General Belgrano, Paraje of La Colonia, in Buenos Aires Province. It is within the surveillance area for livestock anthrax and the last isolation of this pathogen in this partido was in 2005-2006. The carcass was disposed of by incineration.

--
Dr Ramon Noseda
CFO-Director/Microbiologist
Laboratorio Azul Diagnostico SA
Av 25 de Mayo 479
(B 7300 FXE) Azul Bs As
Argentina
http://www.laboratorioazul.com.ar
<rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar>

[Protection from anthrax by vaccination is not long lasting. At best and with a reliable Sterne vaccine it is less than 9 months. Thus, annual livestock vaccinations need to be carefully scheduled to cover the months of usual maximum risk, that is, the hot summer months. Recurrence of the disease following re-exposure occurs in both livestock and humans.

To find General Belgrano go to http://www.fallingrain.com/world/AR/01/General_Belgrano.html. - Mod.MHJ

ProMED thanks Dr Ramon Noseda for this 1st-hand report. - Mod.JW

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8rT0.]
